Tool Calling

Tool calling allows an AI agent to invoke predefined Python functions (tools) when it needs external data or logic to answer a question.

Instead of the model generating responses directly, it can:

Understand the user's query

Decide which tool is relevant

Call the tool

Use the tool's output to generate the final response

This allows the agent to perform real actions using real application logic.

How I Implemented Tool Calling

I created tools using the @function_tool decorator.

Example:

@function_tool
async def list_products(wrapper: RunContextWrapper[StoreContext]) -> str:

This decorator registers the function as a tool that the agent can call.

The agent can then use this function whenever the user asks about available products.

Example Tool: List Products

This tool returns the list of products stored in the application context.

@function_tool
async def list_products(wrapper: RunContextWrapper[StoreContext]) -> str:

    logger.info("Tool called: list_products")

    result = "Available Products:\n"

    for p in wrapper.context.products:
        result += f"- {p.name}: ${p.price}\n"

    return result

The tool accesses the shared StoreContext to retrieve product information.

Example Tool: Calculate Total

This tool calculates the total cost of a product.

@function_tool
async def calculate_total(
    wrapper: RunContextWrapper[StoreContext],
    product_name: str,
    quantity: int
) -> str:

If a user asks something like:

"What is the price of 2 laptops?"

The agent calls this tool and returns the computed result.

RunContextWrapper

Each tool receives a RunContextWrapper object.

RunContextWrapper[StoreContext]

This wrapper gives tools access to the shared application context.

Example:

wrapper.context.products

This allows tools to interact with the application's product data.

Forced Tool Calling

Another important concept I implemented is Forced Tool Calling.

Normally, the agent chooses whether to call a tool or generate an answer itself.

However, in some applications, we want to force the agent to use tools instead of generating responses from the model.

This ensures that the agent always relies on real system data.

Why Forced Tool Calling Is Important

Forced tool usage ensures:

The agent does not hallucinate product information

Responses always come from actual application data

Business logic remains controlled by backend functions

This is especially useful in systems like:

E-commerce

Finance

Inventory systems

Booking platforms

How I Implemented Forced Tool Calling

I used ModelSettings and set tool_choice="required".

model_settings = ModelSettings(
    tool_choice="required"
)

Then I passed it to the agent:

agent = Agent[StoreContext](
    name="Ecommerce Assistant",
    instructions="""
    Always use tools to answer user queries.
    Never generate product data yourself.
    """,
    tools=[list_products, calculate_total],
    model=model,
    model_settings=model_settings
)
What This Means

Setting:

tool_choice="required"

forces the agent to:

Always call one of the available tools

Never generate answers directly

Use backend functions to respond

So the model cannot produce responses like:

❌ "A laptop costs around $1000."

Instead it must call:

calculate_total()

or

list_products()